<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-342-922  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 342 922.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  June 12 1989 v8 n12 p3(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Senate considers super network. (S 1067, the NationalHigh-Performance Computer Technology Act of 1989)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Smith, James M.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Congress. SenateLegislationSupercomputersNetworksResearch and DevelopmentConferences and Meetings.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Senate Considers Super NetworkandM;The Senate will begin hearings next week on abill to provide $1.75 billion tocreate a national network of supercomputers and establish specific goals forthe federal government's effort in supercomputing research and development.andM;The Commerce, Science and Transportation Subcommittee on Science, Technologyand Space has scheduled a hearing June 21 on S 1067, the NationalHigh-Performance Computer Technology Act of 1989.andM;The bill was introduced by Sens.andP;  Albert Gore Jr.andP;  (D-Tenn.) and Ernest F.andO;Hollings (D-S.C.)andM;&quot;We are at the sixth or seventh generation of computer capacity, but only thesecond generatio of networking.andP;  We aren't linked together,&quot; Gore said lastweek.andP;  &quot;We need to leapfrog the Japanese by linking our supercomputerstogether.&quot;andM;The high-speed, high-capacity, fiber-optic data network link the country'shigh-performance computing centers, with &quot;interchanges&quot; that would allowinformation-related businesses and university researchers to communicate,Gore said.andM;The bill calls for the National Institute of Standards and Technology toestablish the standards for such a network.andM;A NIST spokesman, Michael Baum, said, &quot;No doubt we support the basic conceptfor the bill.andP;  NIST definitely considers fiber-optic technology the way ofthe future.andO;</TEXT></DOC>